### RESEARCHER-A Round 1

In this round I verified one solid, dated, primary-source catalyst for an AI-first drug developer: Recursion Pharmaceuticals (RXRX) lists a planned Phase 2 readout for REC‑617 (a CDK7 inhibitor) in Q1 2026 in its SEC filing (https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1601830/000160183025000035/rxrx-20241231.htm?utm_source=openai), which fits inside the September 2026 investment window and can serve as a concrete watchlist entry; next step is to find additional public AI‑driven companies with similarly dated catalysts (trial readouts, FDA decisions, or binding partnership milestones before Q3 2026) using primary IR/SEC/ClinicalTrials.gov sources so the strategy isn’t built on a single data point. (green)

### RESEARCHER-B Round 1

We reviewed recent FDA/EMA materials and agency announcements about AI in drug development and found a clear pattern: regulators are issuing guidance on using AI outputs as part of submissions and building credibility/validation frameworks, but they are not creating a new, faster “AI drug approval” pathway that would short‑circuit clinical testing—see FDA draft guidance Jan 2025 (“Considerations for the Use of Artificial Intelligence to Support Regulatory Decision‑Making for Drug and Biological Products”) (https://www.fda.gov/regulatory-information/search-fda-guidance-documents/considerations-use-artificial-intelligence-support-regulatory-decision-making-drug-and-biological?utm_source=openai) and FDA/EMA “guiding principles of good AI practice” Jan 2026 (https://www.fda.gov/about-fda/artificial-intelligence-drug-development/guiding-principles-good-ai-practice-drug-development?utm_source=openai). The agency is also piloting internal AI‑assisted scientific review and proposing a risk‑based credibility framework for AI models used in submissions—steps that could improve review efficiency or make AI‑derived evidence more acceptable, but not eliminate the need for standard clinical timelines (FDA AI review pilot press release: https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-announces-completion-first-ai-assisted-scientific-review-pilot-and-aggressive-agency-wide-ai?utm_source=openai; credibility framework announcement: https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-proposes-framework-advance-credibility-ai-models-used-drug-and-biological-product-submissions?utm_source=openai). Practical takeaway: regulatory headwinds remain the main limiter for any claim that AI alone will produce tradable drug approvals by Sept 2026—AI may speed discovery and evidence generation, but sponsors still face conventional clinical and regulatory timelines. Vibe check: (yellow) = working but unclear if productive.

### RESEARCHER-C Round 1

This research round gathered three specific, source-backed FDA policy “anchors” (Jan 6, 2025 draft guidance on model credibility; Apr 10, 2025 signals on reduced animal-testing dependency; Feb 18, 2026 reporting on possible single-pivotal-study shifts) and translated them into a tight investment implication: near-term AI value is most likely to materialize through stronger regulatory evidence packages and faster IND-enabling work, not sudden product approvals, so the stocks most likely to move by September 2026 are those with concrete near-term catalysts (upcoming INDs/pivots, published model credibility engagements with FDA, or acceptance of non-animal data) and sufficient cash runway. I documented those anchors and planned to compile a valuation snapshot (price, market cap, 12‑mo returns, cash/burn) for AI-native drug-discovery names (e.g., RXRX and peers) as the next deliverable. One new thing I will try now to make the thesis testable and actionable: build a simple event-driven payoff model that maps (a) probability and timing of FDA-accepting AI-enabled evidence for each company, (b) the company-specific cash runway and upcoming catalysts, and (c) a downside stress case — producing a ranked score of which tickers are plausibly "in-play" before Sep 2026; that score will drive the tiered watchlist and position-size recommendations. (yellow)

